Transparency does not increase image size. It's the way PNG deals with image compression that causes them to be large. PNG is designed for simple color images. You can have a 100kX100k png that is one color and the entire image will be less than 1KB. I used to use single color images as wallpapers that would rotate through and all of them were about 656 bytes.
JPEG does well with compressing images that have a lot of color variations. However jpeg does not support transparency. Take that same single color massive image and make it a JPEG and it will be much larger than the PNG counterpart. The inverse is true if you take a large photo of touching grass, the JPEG will be much smaller than the PNG.
